# React: Performance Optimization Patterns

This rule defines when and how to optimize React component performance. The goal is to prevent unnecessary re-renders while avoiding premature optimization.

## Rationale

- Unnecessary re-renders waste CPU cycles and degrade user experience
- Premature optimization adds complexity without measurable benefit
- Clear patterns help developers make informed optimization decisions
- Consistent use of memoization improves codebase predictability

## Core Principle: Profile Before Optimizing

**DO NOT optimize without measuring first**, except for the strict rules below.

Use React DevTools Profiler to identify:
- Components that re-render frequently
- Expensive render operations
- Unnecessary re-renders in child components

## Strict Rules

### MUST use useCallback for event handlers passed as props

When passing event handlers to child components as props, they MUST be wrapped in useCallback to prevent unnecessary child re-renders.

**Exception:** Event handlers used only within the same component don't need useCallback.

### MUST NOT create inline objects or arrays in props

Inline object literals and array literals in props cause child components to re-render on every parent render.

### MUST NOT create functions in render

Functions created during render have new references every time, breaking memoization.

## Performance Patterns

### ✅ CORRECT - useCallback for event handlers passed as props

```tsx
function EventsPage() {
  const [selectedEvent, setSelectedEvent] = useState<Event | null>(null)
  
  // ✅ Stable function reference with useCallback
  const handleEdit = useCallback((event: Event) => {
    setSelectedEvent(event)
    setDialogOpen(true)
  }, []) // Empty deps - function doesn't depend on external values
  
  const handleDelete = useCallback((event: Event) => {
    setSelectedEvent(event)
    setDeleteDialogOpen(true)
  }, [])
  
  // ✅ Pass stable references to child
  return <EventsTable events={events} onEdit={handleEdit} onDelete={handleDelete} />
}

// Child component can be memoized effectively
const EventsTable = React.memo(function EventsTable({ 
  events, 
  onEdit, 
  onDelete 
}: EventsTableProps) {
  // Won't re-render unless events, onEdit, or onDelete change
  return <table>{/* render events */}</table>
})
```

### ✅ CORRECT - useMemo for expensive computations

```tsx
function EventsPage() {
  const { data: events } = useEvents()
  
  // ✅ Expensive computation - extract unique venues from large list
  const uniqueVenues = useMemo(() => {
    if (!events) return []
    const venuesSet = new Set<string>()
    events.forEach((event) => {
      if (event.venueName?.trim()) {
        venuesSet.add(event.venueName)
      }
    })
    return Array.from(venuesSet).sort()
  }, [events])
  
  // ✅ Expensive filtering operation
  const filteredEvents = useMemo(() => {
    return events?.filter(event => {
      // Complex filtering logic
      return matchesFilters(event, filters)
    }) ?? []
  }, [events, filters])
  
  return <VenueFilter venues={uniqueVenues} />
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - React.memo for expensive components

```tsx
// ✅ Expensive component with stable props
const EventRow = React.memo(function EventRow({ 
  event, 
  onEdit, 
  onDelete 
}: EventRowProps) {
  // Complex rendering logic
  return (
    <tr>
      <td>
        <LazyImage src={event.posterUrl} alt={event.title} width={64} height={64} />
      </td>
      <td>{event.title}</td>
      <td>{format(event.startDate, 'PPP')}</td>
      <td>
        <Button onClick={() => onEdit(event)}>Edit</Button>
        <Button onClick={() => onDelete(event)}>Delete</Button>
      </td>
    </tr>
  )
})

// Usage with stable callbacks
function EventsTable({ events }: { events: Event[] }) {
  const handleEdit = useCallback((event: Event) => {
    // Edit logic
  }, [])
  
  const handleDelete = useCallback((event: Event) => {
    // Delete logic
  }, [])
  
  return (
    <table>
      <tbody>
        {events.map(event => (
          <EventRow 
            key={event.id} 
            event={event} 
            onEdit={handleEdit} 
            onDelete={handleDelete} 
          />
        ))}
      </tbody>
    </table>
  )
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Avoid inline objects in props

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - Inline object creates new reference every render
function EventsPage() {
  return <EventsFilters filters={{ cityId: '123', startDate: Date.now() }} />
}

// ✅ GOOD - Extract to stable reference
function EventsPage() {
  const [filters, setFilters] = useState({ cityId: '123', startDate: Date.now() })
  return <EventsFilters filters={filters} />
}

// ✅ GOOD - Use useMemo for computed objects
function EventsPage() {
  const filters = useMemo(() => ({
    cityId: selectedCity?.id,
    startDate: startDate?.getTime(),
  }), [selectedCity?.id, startDate])
  
  return <EventsFilters filters={filters} />
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Avoid inline arrays in props

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - Inline array creates new reference every render
function EventsPage() {
  return <TagSelector tags={['music', 'sports', 'food']} />
}

// ✅ GOOD - Extract to constant outside component
const DEFAULT_TAGS = ['music', 'sports', 'food']

function EventsPage() {
  return <TagSelector tags={DEFAULT_TAGS} />
}

// ✅ GOOD - Use useMemo for computed arrays
function EventsPage() {
  const { data: events } = useEvents()
  
  const eventIds = useMemo(() => 
    events?.map(e => e.id) ?? [], 
    [events]
  )
  
  return <EventSelector eventIds={eventIds} />
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Stable dependencies in useCallback

```tsx
function EventsPage() {
  const [filters, setFilters] = useState<EventFilters>({})
  const queryClient = useQueryClient()
  
  // ✅ Include all dependencies
  const handleFilterChange = useCallback((newFilters: Partial<EventFilters>) => {
    setFilters(prev => ({ ...prev, ...newFilters }))
    queryClient.invalidateQueries({ queryKey: ['events'] })
  }, [queryClient]) // queryClient is stable from TanStack Query
  
  return <EventsFilters filters={filters} onChange={handleFilterChange} />
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Component composition to avoid prop drilling

```tsx
// ✅ GOOD - Composition avoids passing callbacks through multiple levels
function EventsPage() {
  const [selectedEvent, setSelectedEvent] = useState<Event | null>(null)
  
  const handleEdit = useCallback((event: Event) => {
    setSelectedEvent(event)
  }, [])
  
  return (
    <div>
      {/* Pass data down, hoist callbacks up */}
      <EventsTable events={events}>
        {(event) => (
          <EventRow event={event} onEdit={handleEdit} />
        )}
      </EventsTable>
    </div>
  )
}
```

### ✅ CORRECT - Lazy loading for heavy components

```tsx
import { lazyComponent } from '@/components/lazyComponent'

// ✅ Heavy dialog loaded only when needed
const MergeReviewDialog = lazyComponent(
  () => import('@/components/events/MergeReviewDialog').then(m => ({
    default: m.MergeReviewDialog,
  })),
  { fallback: <div className="p-4">Loading...</div> }
)

function EventsPage() {
  const [mergeDialogOpen, setMergeDialogOpen] = useState(false)
  
  return (
    <>
      <Button onClick={() => setMergeDialogOpen(true)}>Merge Events</Button>
      {/* Only loads when dialog opens */}
      {mergeDialogOpen && <MergeReviewDialog open={mergeDialogOpen} />}
    </>
  )
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Inline function in props

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - New function created every render
function EventsPage() {
  const [selectedEvent, setSelectedEvent] = useState<Event | null>(null)
  
  return (
    <EventsTable 
      events={events}
      onEdit={(event) => {
        setSelectedEvent(event)
        setDialogOpen(true)
      }}
    />
  )
}

// ✅ GOOD - useCallback for stable reference
function EventsPage() {
  const [selectedEvent, setSelectedEvent] = useState<Event | null>(null)
  
  const handleEdit = useCallback((event: Event) => {
    setSelectedEvent(event)
    setDialogOpen(true)
  }, [])
  
  return <EventsTable events={events} onEdit={handleEdit} />
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Unnecessary useMemo

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - Premature optimization for simple computation
function EventCard({ event }: { event: Event }) {
  const title = useMemo(() => event.title.toUpperCase(), [event.title])
  // ❌ toUpperCase() is cheap, useMemo adds overhead
  
  return <h2>{title}</h2>
}

// ✅ GOOD - Simple computation doesn't need memoization
function EventCard({ event }: { event: Event }) {
  const title = event.title.toUpperCase()
  return <h2>{title}</h2>
}
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Unnecessary React.memo

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - Simple component with cheap render
const SimpleButton = React.memo(function SimpleButton({ label }: { label: string }) {
  return <button>{label}</button>
})
// ❌ Memo overhead > render cost

// ✅ GOOD - No memo for simple components
function SimpleButton({ label }: { label: string }) {
  return <button>{label}</button>
}

// ✅ GOOD - Memo for expensive components
const ComplexEventCard = React.memo(function ComplexEventCard({ event }: { event: Event }) {
  // Expensive rendering with images, formatting, calculations
  return (
    <div>
      <LazyImage src={event.posterUrl} />
      {/* Complex layout and calculations */}
    </div>
  )
})
```

### ❌ INCORRECT - Missing dependencies in useCallback

```tsx
// ❌ BAD - Missing dependency (filters)
function EventsPage() {
  const [filters, setFilters] = useState<EventFilters>({})
  
  const handleSearch = useCallback((query: string) => {
    setFilters({ ...filters, search: query }) // ❌ Uses stale filters
  }, []) // ❌ Missing filters dependency
  
  return <SearchInput onSearch={handleSearch} />
}

// ✅ GOOD - Include all dependencies
function EventsPage() {
  const [filters, setFilters] = useState<EventFilters>({})
  
  const handleSearch = useCallback((query: string) => {
    setFilters(prev => ({ ...prev, search: query })) // ✅ Use updater function
  }, []) // ✅ No external dependencies needed
  
  return <SearchInput onSearch={handleSearch} />
}

// ✅ ALTERNATIVE - Include dependency
function EventsPage() {
  const [filters, setFilters] = useState<EventFilters>({})
  
  const handleSearch = useCallback((query: string) => {
    setFilters({ ...filters, search: query })
  }, [filters]) // ✅ Include filters (but recreates callback when filters change)
  
  return <SearchInput onSearch={handleSearch} />
}
```

## When to Use Each Optimization

### Use React.memo when:
- Component has expensive render logic (complex calculations, many elements)
- Component receives stable props most of the time
- Component is rendered frequently with same props
- Profiling shows unnecessary re-renders

### Use useMemo when:
- Computation is expensive (filtering large arrays, complex calculations)
- Result is used in dependency arrays of other hooks
- Result is passed as prop to memoized child components
- Profiling shows computation is a bottleneck

### Use useCallback when:
- Function is passed as prop to child components (REQUIRED)
- Function is used in dependency arrays of other hooks
- Function is passed to memoized components

### DON'T optimize when:
- Component renders are cheap (< 1ms)
- Props change frequently anyway
- Component is rarely rendered
- You haven't profiled to confirm the issue

## Performance Checklist

### ✅ DO

- Profile with React DevTools before optimizing
- Use useCallback for all event handlers passed as props
- Avoid inline objects and arrays in props
- Use useMemo for expensive computations (filtering large lists)
- Use React.memo for expensive components with stable props
- Lazy load heavy components (charts, dialogs, editors)
- Extract constants outside components
- Use updater functions in setState to avoid dependencies

### ❌ DON'T

- Don't optimize without measuring first
- Don't use React.memo on every component
- Don't use useMemo for cheap computations
- Don't create inline functions in props
- Don't create inline objects/arrays in props
- Don't forget dependencies in useCallback/useMemo
- Don't over-optimize at the expense of readability

## Measuring Performance

### Use React DevTools Profiler

```tsx
// Wrap component to profile
import { Profiler } from 'react'

function EventsPage() {
  return (
    <Profiler id="EventsPage" onRender={(id, phase, actualDuration) => {
      console.log(`${id} (${phase}) took ${actualDuration}ms`)
    }}>
      {/* component content */}
    </Profiler>
  )
}
```

### Performance Budgets

- Initial page load: < 3s
- Time to Interactive: < 5s
- Component render: < 16ms (60fps)
- Expensive computation: < 100ms

## PR Checklist

- [ ] All event handlers passed as props use useCallback
- [ ] No inline objects or arrays in props
- [ ] No functions created in render
- [ ] Expensive computations use useMemo
- [ ] Heavy components are lazy loaded
- [ ] React.memo used only for expensive components
- [ ] Performance optimizations are justified by profiling (except strict rules)

## Exceptions

- Prototypes and POCs may skip optimizations temporarily
- Simple components (< 10 elements) rarely need optimization
- Components that always re-render (due to changing props) don't benefit from memo

